    "summary": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Assuming that something true of a thing must also be true of all or some of its parts.",
        "spans": []
      }
    ],
    "description": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Some properties are such that, if a whole object has the property, then all of its parts will, too—for example, invisibility. However, not all properties are like this—for instance, visibility. Let's call a property which distributes from a whole object to each of its parts a \"dissective\" property, using Nelson Goodman's term. If P is a dissective property, then the argument form above is validating, by definition of what such a property is. However, if P is not dissective, then the argument form is non-validating, and any argument of that form commits the fallacy of Division.",
        "spans": [
